

<% title = "Menstrual Cycle Tracking | Women's Health & Wellness" %>

<link rel="stylesheet" href="/static/css/calendar.css" />

<section class="section" style="background-color: var(--light-color)">
  <div class="container">
    <h1 class="text-center mb-4">Menstrual Cycle Tracking</h1>
    <p class="text-center mb-5">
      Track your menstrual cycle to better understand your body's patterns and
      optimize your health planning.
    </p>

    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-lg-8">
        <div class="calendar-container">
          <div class="calendar-header">
            <h3>Your Menstrual Calendar</h3>
            <p>Click and drag on the calendar to mark your period days.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="calendar-content">
            <div id="menstrual-calendar"></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="col-lg-4">
        <div class="tracking-form">
          <h3>Record Your Period</h3>
          <form id="period-form">
            <div class="form-group">
              <label for="period-start" class="form-label">Start Date</label>
              <input
                type="date"
                class="form-control"
                id="period-start"
                required
              />
            </div>

            <div class="form-group">
              <label for="period-end" class="form-label">End Date</label>
              <input type="date" class="form-control" id="period-end" />
            </div>

            <div class="form-group">
              <label for="flow-level" class="form-label">Flow Level</label>
              <select class="form-control" id="flow-level">
                <option value="light">Light</option>
                <option value="medium" selected>Medium</option>
                <option value="heavy">Heavy</option>
              </select>
            </div>

            <div class="form-group">
              <label for="symptoms" class="form-label">Symptoms</label>
              <input
                type="text"
                class="form-control"
                id="symptoms"
                placeholder="e.g., cramps, headache, bloating"
              />
            </div>

            <div class="form-group">
              <label for="notes" class="form-label">Notes</label>
              <textarea
                class="form-control"
                id="notes"
                rows="3"
                placeholder="Additional notes about your cycle"
              ></textarea>
            </div>

            <button
              type="button"
              id="save-period"
              class="btn btn-primary w-100"
            >
              Save Period Data
            </button>
          </form>
        </div>

        <div class="info-card mt-4">
          <div class="info-card-content">
            <h4>Understanding Flow Levels</h4>
            <div class="flow-level-indicator">
              <div class="flow-level-dot flow-light"></div>
              <span>Light - Spotting or minimal flow</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flow-level-indicator">
              <div class="flow-level-dot flow-medium"></div>
              <span>Medium - Moderate flow</span>
            </div>
            <div class="flow-level-indicator">
              <div class="flow-level-dot flow-heavy"></div>
              <span>Heavy - Requires frequent product changes</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-lg-8">
        <h2 class="mb-4">Understanding Your Menstrual Cycle</h2>

        <h4>The Four Phases of Your Cycle</h4>
        <p>
          A complete menstrual cycle typically lasts between 21 to 35 days, with
          the average being 28 days. It consists of four main phases:
        </p>

        <div class="card mb-4">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h5 class="card-title">1. Menstruation Phase (Days 1-5)</h5>
            <p class="card-text">
              This is when your period occurs as the uterine lining is shed. The
              first day of bleeding marks day 1 of your cycle. Common symptoms
              include:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>Cramps</li>
              <li>Bloating</li>
              <li>Breast tenderness</li>
              <li>Mood changes</li>
              <li>Fatigue</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="card mb-4">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h5 class="card-title">2. Follicular Phase (Days 1-13)</h5>
            <p class="card-text">
              This phase overlaps with menstruation and continues until
              ovulation. During this time:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>Follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) rises</li>
              <li>Follicles in the ovaries develop</li>
              <li>Estrogen levels increase</li>
              <li>The uterine lining begins to thicken</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="card mb-4">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h5 class="card-title">
              3. Ovulation Phase (Day 14, approximately)
            </h5>
            <p class="card-text">
              This is when a mature egg is released from the ovary into the
              fallopian tube. Signs of ovulation may include:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>Slight increase in basal body temperature</li>
              <li>Clear, stretchy cervical mucus (similar to egg whites)</li>
              <li>Mild pain or cramping on one side of the lower abdomen</li>
              <li>Increased libido</li>
              <li>Slight spotting</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="card mb-4">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h5 class="card-title">4. Luteal Phase (Days 15-28)</h5>
            <p class="card-text">
              This final phase occurs after ovulation and before your next
              period. During this phase:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>The empty follicle forms the corpus luteum</li>
              <li>Progesterone levels rise</li>
              <li>PMS symptoms may appear</li>
              <li>If pregnancy doesn't occur, hormone levels drop</li>
              <li>The uterine lining prepares to shed</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="col-lg-4">
        <div class="info-card">
          <div class="info-card-content">
            <h4>Benefits of Tracking Your Cycle</h4>
            <ul class="list-group list-group-flush">
              <li class="list-group-item">Predict your next period</li>
              <li class="list-group-item">Identify patterns in symptoms</li>
              <li class="list-group-item">
                Plan around your cycle for important events
              </li>
              <li class="list-group-item">
                Understand fertility windows if trying to conceive
              </li>
              <li class="list-group-item">
                Recognize irregular patterns that may need medical attention
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="info-card mt-4">
          <div class="info-card-content">
            <h4>When to See a Doctor</h4>
            <p>Consider consulting a healthcare provider if you experience:</p>
            <ul class="list-group list-group-flush">
              <li class="list-group-item">
                Periods that last longer than 7 days
              </li>
              <li class="list-group-item">
                Very heavy bleeding (soaking through a pad/tampon every hour)
              </li>
              <li class="list-group-item">
                Severe pain that interferes with daily activities
              </li>
              <li class="list-group-item">
                Missed periods (if not on birth control or pregnant)
              </li>
              <li class="list-group-item">
                Irregular cycles that suddenly change
              </li>
              <li class="list-group-item">Bleeding between periods</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" style="background-color: var(--light-color)">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="text-center mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="accordion" id="faqAccordion">
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingOne">
          <button
            class="accordion-button"
            type="button"
            data-bs-toggle="collapse"
            data-bs-target="#collapseOne"
            aria-expanded="true"
            aria-controls="collapseOne"
          >
            What is a "normal" menstrual cycle?
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div
          id="collapseOne"
          class="accordion-collapse collapse show"
          aria-labelledby="headingOne"
          data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion"
        >
          <div class="accordion-body">
            A normal menstrual cycle can range from 21 to 35 days, with the
            average being 28 days. The period itself typically lasts 3-7 days.
            However, what's "normal" varies from person to person, and your own
            normal may change throughout your life.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingTwo">
          <button
            class="accordion-button collapsed"
            type="button"
            data-bs-toggle="collapse"
            data-bs-target="#collapseTwo"
            aria-expanded="false"
            aria-controls="collapseTwo"
          >
            Why is my period irregular?
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div
          id="collapseTwo"
          class="accordion-collapse collapse"
          aria-labelledby="headingTwo"
          data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion"
        >
          <div class="accordion-body">
            Irregular periods can be caused by many factors including stress,
            significant weight changes, excessive exercise, hormonal imbalances,
            polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), thyroid disorders, perimenopause,
            and certain medications. If your periods are consistently irregular,
            it's best to consult with a healthcare provider.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingThree">
          <button
            class="accordion-button collapsed"
            type="button"
            data-bs-toggle="collapse"
            data-bs-target="#collapseThree"
            aria-expanded="false"
            aria-controls="collapseThree"
          >
            How can tracking help with family planning?
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div
          id="collapseThree"
          class="accordion-collapse collapse"
          aria-labelledby="headingThree"
          data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion"
        >
          <div class="accordion-body">
            Tracking your menstrual cycle can help identify your fertile
            window—the days when you're most likely to conceive. This
            information can be useful both for those trying to conceive and
            those wanting to avoid pregnancy. However, cycle tracking alone is
            not considered a reliable form of birth control.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingFour">
          <button
            class="accordion-button collapsed"
            type="button"
            data-bs-toggle="collapse"
            data-bs-target="#collapseFour"
            aria-expanded="false"
            aria-controls="collapseFour"
          >
            Can menstrual cycle tracking help identify health issues?
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div
          id="collapseFour"
          class="accordion-collapse collapse"
          aria-labelledby="headingFour"
          data-bs-parent="#faqAccordion"
        >
          <div class="accordion-body">
            Yes, tracking can help identify patterns that might indicate
            underlying health issues. For example, consistently heavy or painful
            periods might suggest conditions like endometriosis or fibroids.
            Very irregular cycles could indicate hormonal imbalances or PCOS.
            Sharing your tracking data with your healthcare provider can be
            valuable for diagnosing conditions.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

